{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:19:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19188"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19188"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.06,0.72,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81930"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19188"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"9635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27939"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81930"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent concerned about his height. His height has increased by 9 cm over the past year. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Both parents are tall - his parent is 188 cm and their partner is 182 cm tall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His height is 172 cm (\u003E97th centile) and weight 65 kg (90th centile). His arm span to height ratio is 1.0. He has Tanner stage 2 pubic hair development and testicular volume of 8 mL bilaterally. There are no dysmorphic features. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Klinefelter syndrome","Marfan syndrome","Growth hormone excess","Constitutional tall stature","Precocious puberty"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Econstitutional tall stature\u003C/strong\u003E. Key supporting features include tall parents (suggesting genetic predisposition), normal body proportions, and age-appropriate pubertal development. His growth velocity of 9 cm/year is within normal limits for a boy at Tanner stage 2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMarfan syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E would present with increased arm span to height ratio (\u003E1.05), joint hypermobility, lens dislocation, and cardiac manifestations. The normal body proportions and absence of characteristic features make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlinefelter syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (47,XXY karyotype) classically presents with tall stature, but is typically accompanied by small firm testes (\u003C4 mL), delayed puberty, gynaecomastia, and neurodevelopmental difficulties. This patient\u0027s normal testicular volume makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone excess\u003C/strong\u003E from pituitary pathology would manifest with more dramatic height acceleration, acral enlargement, prognathism, and symptoms of mass effect such as headache or visual field defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrecocious puberty\u003C/strong\u003E is excluded by the age-appropriate onset of puberty. While it can cause tall stature in childhood, it typically results in reduced final adult height due to premature epiphyseal fusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConstitutional tall stature requires exclusion of pathological causes through careful history, examination and selected investigations. The pattern of growth should be monitored, but specific intervention is rarely required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Constitutional tall stature is the most common cause of tall stature in children and is diagnosed by excluding pathological causes.","Growth velocity and bone age are essential investigations in evaluating tall stature.","Klinefelter syndrome should be considered in boys with tall stature, particularly if associated with delayed puberty or learning difficulties."],"references":["Kumar S. Tall stature in children: differential diagnosis and management. Int J Pediatr Endocrinol. 2013;2013(Suppl 1):P53. doi: 10.1186/1687-9856-2013-S1-P53. Epub 2013 Oct 3. PMCID: PMC3850425."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67199"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19188"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67199"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T13:21:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T13:26:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81930"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"